***Introduction***

In an ongoing effort to improve the work-life balance of our employees,
our company decided to look at our shiftwork schedules. The goal is to
ensure that we are offering the best possible work schedules for our
employees while meeting the needs of our customers.

We looked to Shiftwork Solutions for help in the Evaluation, Design, and
Implementation of our current schedule and/or any new schedule. This
document is the end result of their study.

After looking at things such as Shift Start Times, Overtime and Schedule
Patterns, it has been determined that the schedule options contained in
this document represent the best possible solutions for our employees.
The final decision will be based on your input using the process
described below.

***Schedule Selection Process***

In mid-2020, we will be implementing a 24/7 schedule on 2 or 3 of the
Saltine Lines. The number of lines we implement on will be determined by
the customer demand at the time of implementation along with the
preferences of the workforce.

The selection process will answer the two following questions:

1.  What will be the schedules be for the Day Shift and for the Night
    Shift when we go 24/7 on some of our Saltine lines?

2.  Which shift and schedule would you prefer to be assigned to?

Everyone will have a few days to review the contents of this document
before using the last page (Preference Form) to let the company know
which schedule and shifts you most prefer. The forms need to be
submitted to the Human Resource Department no later than 8:00 am on
Tuesday, December 17^th^.

**[24/7 Schedule Options]{.underline}*: ***

There are 2 Day shift patterns to choose from as well as 2 Night shift
patterns to choose from. The Day shift pattern and the Night shift
pattern DO NOT need to be the same pattern.

[The Day Shift Patterns:]{.underline}

Option #1 is the 2-3-2 pattern with every other weekend off as a 3-day
weekend.

Option #2 is the 4/3 pattern which is the same pattern currently being
worked by maintenance.

[The Night Shift Patterns:]{.underline}

Option #1 is the 3-on-3-off pattern where you work 3 weekends in a row
and then get three weekends off in a row.

Option #2 is the 4/3 pattern which is the same pattern currently being
worked by maintenance.

**Current Schedule (Saltines)**

**13 workdays in a row then 1 day off (8-hour shifts)**

![](media/image2.emf)

**How the schedule works**

In the schedule above, an "8" represents an 8-hour shift.

This schedule has a 2-week cycle. In the first week, you work seven
days, Sunday through Saturday. Rotating down to the second week, you
work six days in a row, Sunday -- Friday. Following the stretch of 13
days of work in a row, you get one day off on Saturday.

Variations may include having a day off other than Saturday. This
schedule represents "peak" season and is not generally expected to be
used year-round.

**24/7 Coverage Day Shift Option #1: 2-3-2**

**Every Other Weekend Off**

![](media/image3.emf)

**How the schedule works**

In the schedule above, an "D12" represents a 12-hour Day shift from 6:00
am until 6:00 pm. The Key Feature is that every other weekend is off as
a 3-day weekend.

There are two weeks in this schedule's cycle. The two crews on Days will
each start in a different week.

Starting in week 1, the 2-week cycle will look like this:

Sunday is off. Work 12-hour shifts on Monday and Tuesday. Take off
Wednesday and Thursday. Work Friday and Saturday.

Rotate down to week 2.

Work Sunday. Take off Monday and Tuesday. Work Wednesday and Thursday.
Take off Friday and Saturday.

Rotate up to week 1 and take Sunday off as you begin the cycle again.

In this way, you have every other weekend off as a 3-day weekend
(Friday, Saturday and Sunday off).

**24/7 Coverage Day Shift Option #2: 4-3 pattern**

![](media/image4.emf)

**How the schedule works**

In the schedule above, an "D12" represents a 12-hour Day shift from 6:00
am until 6:00 pm. The Key Feature is that you have the same days of work
and the same days off every week (with the exception of Wednesdays which
are worked on alternating weeks).

This Day shift schedule is staffed using 2 crews. Crew A rotates through
the top two-week pattern and Crew B rotates through the bottom two-week
pattern.

[Going through a 2-week cycle for Crew A]{.underline}

Crew A starts in week 1 and works Sunday, Monday and Tuesday. The crew
then takes off Wednesday through Saturday before rotating down to week
2.

Crew A, now in week 2, works Sunday through Wednesday. The crew then
takes off Thursday, Friday, and Saturday before rotating back up to week
1 and starting all over again.

[Going through a 2-week cycle for Crew B]{.underline}

Crew B starts in week 1 and is off Sunday, Monday and Tuesday. The crew
then works Wednesday through Saturday before rotating down to week 2.

Crew B, now in week 2, is off Sunday through Wednesday. The crew then
works Thursday, Friday and Saturday before rotating back up to week 1
and starting all over again.

**24/7 Coverage Night Shift Option #1: 3-on-3-off modified**

![](media/image5.emf)

**How the schedule works**

In the schedule above, an "N12" represents a 12-hour Night shift from
6:00 pm until 6:00 am. Nights start on the day showed and get off the
following morning. The Key Feature is that you mostly work 3 days in a
row followed by 3 days off. There is one place where you work 2 days in
a row and another where you work 4 days in a row. This is done to give
you full weekends off.

There are 6 weeks in this schedule's cycle. The two crews on Nights will
each start 3 weeks apart. For example, if crew C starts in week 1, then
Crew D will start in week 4.

Starting in week 1, the 6-week cycle will look like this:

Week 1: Start Sunday night at 6:00 pm and work 12 hours. Work Monday
night and Tuesday night; getting off on Wednesday morning. Take off
Wednesday, Thursday and Friday; returning to work Saturday night at 6:00
pm. Rotate down to week 2.

Week 2: Work Sunday and Monday nights; ending at 6:00 am Tuesday
morning. Take off Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday, returning to work
Friday night. Work Friday and Saturday night. Rotate down to week 3.

Week 3: Work Sunday night. Take off Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday;
returning to work Thursday night. Work Friday night and take off
Saturday night. Rotate down to week 4.

Week 4: Take off Sunday through Tuesday; returning to work Wednesday
night. Work Wednesday, Thursday and Friday night. Take off Saturday and
rotate down to week 5.

Week 5: Take off Sunday and Monday. Work Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday
night. Take off Friday and Saturday night. Rotate down to week 6.

Week 6: Take off Sunday. Work Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday nights. Take
off Thursday and Friday; returning to work Saturday night. Work Saturday
night then rotate up to week 1.

