and starting all over again.

**Questions and Answers**

**[Question #1:]{.underline}** What are our options?

**[Answer #1:]{.underline}** There are two options for each shift going
to a 24/7 schedule.

1.  Day Shift

    a.  Option #1: 2-3-2 pattern (Every other weekend off)

    b.  Option #2: 4-3 pattern (Same days off)

2.  Night Shift

    a.  Option #1: 3-on-3-off modified (Work 3 weekends, off 3 weekends)

    b.  Option #2: 4-3 pattern (Same days off)

**[Question #2:]{.underline}** Who has to go to the 24/7 schedule and
when will the schedule be implemented?

**[Answer #2:]{.underline}** We plan on taking at least 2, and possibly
3 of the saltine lines to 24/7 operations. To support the lines, we will
need to take some of the people in Mixing to a 24/7 schedule as well.

**[Question #3:]{.underline}** I work in an area that is already working
a 24/7, 12-hour schedule. Will we need to change?

**[Answer #3:]{.underline}** No. Those currently on 24/7, 12-hour
schedules rated those schedules very high. They will be kept in place,
unchanged.

**[Question #4:]{.underline}** If I'm in Wirecuts or Sandwiches, will I
have to change? Can we change if we want to?

**[Answer #4:]{.underline}** The only change planned is for 2 or 3 of
the Saltine lines along with enough people from Mixing to support the
change. We will be adding people to our facility in order to staff the
new schedules. If current employees want to go to the new schedules, we
will try to accommodate them. If we cannot fully staff the Saltine lines
with current employees, we will fill the openings with new hires. In
short, we will place current employees where they want to go (so far as
we are able) and then hire into the openings that are left, wherever
they may be.

**[Question #5:]{.underline}** Will there be any changes to any other
areas?

**[Answer #5:]{.underline}** No. We considered starting Wirecuts on
Sunday nights instead of Monday nights but the surveys showed that less
than half of you thought that was a good idea. Additionally, when we
asked about the shift times for the 8-hour shifts, most of you preferred
to keep things as they are.

**[Question #6:]{.underline}** How will the new schedule be chosen?

**[Answer #6:]{.underline}** On the Preference Form at the end of this
document, you will tell us what 24/7 patterns you most prefer for Day
and Night shift. You will also tell us if you want to go those patterns
and on which shift. We will implement the schedule that has the most
support from the affect employees.

**[Question #7:]{.underline}** How will it be decided who goes to what
shift?

**[Answer #7:]{.underline}** We will use the following criteria:

1.  People assigned to a line/area will have priority to stay on that
    line/area.

2.  People currently on Day shift will have first priority to stay on
    Day shift.

3.  Where do you want to go? (as expressed on the Preference Form at the
    end of this document)

4.  How long have you worked here?

5.  What are you already qualified to do?

6.  Performance and attendance.

**[Question #8]{.underline}**: When will we know our new schedule?

**[Answer #8:]{.underline}** The new schedule will be announced sometime
in January. This includes letting people know what shift they will be
assigned to.

**[Question #8]{.underline}**: Why is attendance one of the criteria to
be considered when placing people on a schedule or shift?

**[Answer #8:]{.underline}** The whole idea behind implementing a
12-hour, 24/7 schedule is to let our lines to keep running while giving
people time off. A 12-hour schedule provides 78 more annual days off
than an 8-hour schedule that works Monday through Friday. A 12-hour
schedule provides 158 more annual days off than an 8-hour 13&1 schedule.
However, if people on the 12-hour schedules call off and have high
absenteeism, this will cause others to come in on days that they
expected to have off. In order to meet people's expectations of more
days off on 12-hour schedules, we want to staff our crews with people
that have the best attendance possible.

To be clear, we expect you to stay at home when you are sick. We also
expect you to enjoy your vacation time. However, high absenteeism beyond
that is not suitable for the 12-hour schedules.

**[Question #9]{.underline}**: When will overtime be paid on the 24/7
schedule?

**[Answer #9:]{.underline}**

If the 12-hour schedule is implemented:

1.  Overtime at time and one-half will be paid for all hours worked
    outside of your regularly scheduled hours, if you work all of your
    regularly scheduled hours.

2.  Overtime at time and one-half will be paid for all hours worked over
    40 in a week.

3.  Double-time will be paid for all hours worked in excess of 60 hours
    during a workweek.

**[Question #10:]{.underline}** When we are scheduled for 12-hour
shifts, can we be made to work more than 12 hours in a day?

**[Answer #10:]{.underline}** Our goal will be to have no one working
more than 12 hours in a day. There may be times when a brief meeting or
something of that nature overrides this goal but in general, a 12-hour
day is all you will be required to work.

**[Question #11:]{.underline}** How will vacation work?

**[Answer #11:]{.underline}** On the 12-hour schedules, vacation will be
taken and paid in hours. If you miss a 12-hour shift, you will be paid
for 12 hours and 12 hours will be charged to your account. On 12-hour
schedules, it is often seen as beneficial to take off a "block" of days.
A "block" is defined as a group of consecutive days of work that are
proceeded and followed by a group of days off. If you choose to take a
"block" off, you will not be subjected to mandatory overtime on the days
off immediately preceding and following your vacation days.

**[Question #12]{.underline}**: How will the new schedules affect my
income?

**[Answer #12:]{.underline}** It depends on how much overtime you work.

Your current schedule averages 40 hours a week with 40 hours of pay.
This is before unscheduled overtime.

The 12-hour schedule averages 42 hours of work per week and 44 hours of
pay before unscheduled overtime.

So, if you don't work any unscheduled overtime the 12-hour schedule will
pay 10% more than your current schedule. (See *Appendix B* for pay
calculations).

Now, on a 13&1, 8-hour schedule, there is a lot of additional overtime
and thus, a lot more pay. This schedule averages 52 hours of work per
week and 60 hours of pay. See *Appendix C* to see how much you would
earn if you worked an equivalent number of hours on a 12-hour schedule.

**[Question #14:]{.underline}** How will holidays work?

**[Answer #14:]{.underline}** There are three considerations surrounding
holidays: (1) Will we work them, (2) What is the **holiday premium** if
I work on a holiday and (3) What is the **holiday pay** if I don't work
on a holiday. Let's take these one at a time:

**Will we work on a holiday?** That depends on the needs of the
business. Take a look at how often we have worked on a holiday in the
past and use that as a guide. We'd like to take every holiday off but
sometimes we will need to run some line.

**What is the rate of pay if I work on a holiday?** You will be paid
double-time for all hours worked on a holiday. This is in addition to
holiday pay (below). Pay for hours worked on a holiday is referred to as
***Holiday Premium***. Note that [Holiday Premium]{.underline} is
different from [Holiday Pay]{.underline} (below).

**What is the rate of holiday pay?** Holiday pay for the 12-hour
schedules will depend if a holiday falls on a scheduled day off or on a
scheduled workday. If a holiday falls on a regularly scheduled day off,
you will get 8 hours of holiday pay. If a holiday falls on a scheduled
workday, you will get 12 hours of holiday pay. See *Appendix D* for
Holiday Pay calculations.

**[Question #15]{.underline}**: On the 12-hour schedule, if I volunteer
to work overtime on a day off, does it have to be for 12 hours?

**[Answer #15]{.underline}**: No. Being flexible on how long an overtime
shift must be is one of the advantages of a 12-hour schedule. So long as
it is manageable, and agreed to in advance with your supervisor, the
number of hours you will work, we want to be flexible.

If several people want overtime, it will be first offered to those that
are willing to work the entire 12-hour shift.

**[Question #15]{.underline}**: If I'm on the 12-hour schedule, can I be
made to work overtime on a non-12-hour schedule?

**[Answer #15]{.underline}**: No. Here is how overtime will work:

1.  If overtime is required on a 12-hour line, it will first be offered
    to volunteers on the 12-hour line. If there are no volunteers, we
    may look for volunteers from the 8-hour line.

2.  If there are not enough volunteers to cover an opening on a 12-hour
    line, then it will be the responsibility of the 12-hour line crew
    that is off to provide coverage.

